# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dexter-s-kimball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-davison-bailey] Bailey was born in what is now Salem Lakes, Wisconsin, son of Eugene M.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-davison-bailey] He obtained his BSc in Mechanical Engineering in 1903 from the Lewis Institute in Chicago, now Illinois Institute of Technology.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-davison-bailey] Before his graduation Bailey had started his career as draftsman at the U.S Wind Engine and Pump Company in Batavia, Illinois, and had been trouble man at the Evanston Heating Co. in Evanston, Illinois.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-davison-bailey] After his graduation Bailey started his lifelong career at the Chicago Edison Co., soon to be Commonwealth Edison.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-davison-bailey] From 1903 to 1905 he started as draftsman, from 1906 to 1916 he was assistant chief engineer at Fisk Street Station, and another chief engineer.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-davison-bailey] From 1921 to 1932 he was superintendent of generating stations of the company, and in 1933 appointed assistant chief operating engineer.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-davison-bailey] From 1936 to 1942 he was chief operating engineer and manager of the Super Power department.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-davison-bailey] The last years ten years at the company he was vice-president in charge of operations and engineering.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-davison-bailey] He retired on February 1, 1952 after 48 years of service.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-davison-bailey] In 1942 Bailey had been awarded the Honorary Doctor of Science by the Northwestern University.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-dow] Dow was born in Glasgow, Scotland as son of William Dow, a blacksmith, and Jean (Keppy) Dow in 1862.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-dow] He emigrated to the US in 1882 at the age of twenty.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-dow] In 1893 Dow was appointed the first plant manager of the first municipally owned power plant in Detroit, and electrical engineer for the city of Detroit.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-dow] The power plant had been built as a result of Hazen Pingree's efforts to break the power of corporations over Detroit City politics.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-dow] It was during this time that Henry Ford worked under Dow at one of the Detroit Edison substations.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-dow] Dow took Ford with him to the 1896 annual convention of the Association of Edison Illuminating Companies being held that year in New York City.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-dow] It was at this convention that Dow introduced Ford to Thomas Edison, the meeting with, and encouragement from, the great scientist becoming a great inspiration to Ford in completing his first car.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-dow] Dow was appointed water commissioner for the city of Detroit in 1916-1921 and again in 1925-1932.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-dow] In 1932, he was made the president of Detroit Edison and served until 1940.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-dow] He was elected president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers for the 1928-1929 year.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-dow] He was a member of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, American Society of Civil Engineers, American Institute of Electrical Engineers, Institute of Electrical Engineers (Great Britain), Institute of Mechanical Engineers (Great Britain).
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alex-dow] Dow also served as the President of The Engineering Society of Detroit from 1900-1901.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was born in Edinburgh, Scotland on 30 March 1851 to Edward Rupert Humphreys, an English classical scholar and profound educator, and Margaret McNutt of Prince Edward Island.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He attended his father's school in Boston after coming to the United States in 1859.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] At the age of fourteen he received an appointment and passed preliminary entrance exams for the United States Naval Academy before the academy discovered he was too young to complete entrance.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He instead began working for insurance companies and was made Secretary-Treasurer of the New York Guaranty and Indemnity Company by 1872, he became superintendent shortly thereafter.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He later became superintendent of the Bayonne and Greenville Gas Light Company and attended Stevens Institute of Technology earning his degree in mechanical engineering; he graduated in 1881.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1892 he founded Humphreys & Glasgow, Engineering, London and New York with Arthur G.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys continued his career with the Pintsch Lighting Company of New York, the United Gas Improvement Company, and the Weisbach Incandescent Gas Company.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In April 1872 he married Miss Eva Guillandeu of Bergen Point, NJ.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] They had three children in total: Harold, Crombie and Dorothy Caroline Humphreys-Turnbull.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of his son Harold, who was also the first son of a Stevens alumnus to graduate from the college, he endowed the Harold Humphreys Scholarship in 1902.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of Crombie, who drowned with Harold in the Nile in 1901, the Crombie Humphreys Scholarship in 1904.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1927, Alexander Crombie Humphreys lost a battle with cancer.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] His death came two years after serving as President of his Alma mater for a quarter of a century, and chairman of the board of trustees for two years.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] The only immediate family member to outlive him was his daughter.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Following the death of Henry Morton in 1902, the board of trustees of Stevens Institute of Technology unanimously called upon Humphreys to serve his Alma mater as president.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Prior to his presidency, Humphreys was elected a trustee of the institute on 23 December 1891 and served as chair of the Stevens Alumni Association from 1883 to 1886.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys developed the institute as one of the first technical schools in the United States.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During a dinner following his inauguration, Colonel Edwin A.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, Jr., son of the school's founder Edwin A.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, presented the institute with a plot of land on which to construct a dormitory.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon assuming the office of President, Humphreys requested of Andrew Carnegie the financial support to construct a new building.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He followed this with an address to the Board of Trustees urging construction of the Morton Laboratory of Chemistry, a dormitory, a gymnasium and library – a "crying need of the Institute".
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] As a homage to his predecessor, Humphreys campaigned for the creation of the Morton Memorial Chemistry Laboratory and commissioned a book on Stevens' founding and its early years to be named in his honor.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] These initiatives were but foreshadowing of the growth Humphreys would bring to Stevens.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1924 the campus grew from just over a city block to 23-acres, enrollment quadrupled and endowment grew to $2,864,000 (from $384,800 when Humprheys took office).
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] That year also marked the successful end of the "Million Dollar Campaign", which had attracted donations from alumni as well as George Eastman and Edward Harkness.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1909, Stevens seized the opportunity to acquire Castle Point from Richard Stevens inclusive of the prominent Stevens Family Castle constructed in 1853; the purchase was primarily funded by the Carnegie Foundation and John D.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] This came within months of acquiring the land adjacent to present-day 8th street upon which fraternity houses were constructed that stand to this day.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1960 the Institute expanded again and constructed two residence halls, one of which bared his name.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the growth of the institute, Alexander C.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys felt it important to impart engineering students with a sense of business – a tool that would be essential in their success in all lines of manufacturing.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He began teaching the first courses on this topic in 1903 and is regarded as the father of Engineering Economics.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] To honor his contributions, Stevens Institute of Technology endows an Alexander Crombie Humphreys Chair in Economics of Engineering.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the dinner of his inauguration, Humphreys announced that one of his ambitions was to start an Honor System at Stevens to cover academic work.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was very adamant that the creation of such a system come from the students and on the first page of the first issue of the school newspaper "The Stute" appeared an article written by a junior urging the implementation of such.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1908 the students created a self run Honor Board who was charged with investigating cases, bringing up charges, judging cases by a vote and recommend punishments to the faculty.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon Humphreys' recommendation, faculty were also required to abide by such a pledge in administering exams within Honor Board guidelines on the grounds that it is a "...proviso apply[ing] to the examiner as well as to the student".
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-graham-christie] Christie was born in Manchester, Ontario, Canada to Peter Christie and Mary Honor (Graham) Christie.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-graham-christie] He obtained his MSc in mechanical engineering at the School of Practical Science at the University of Toronto in 1901.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-graham-christie] After his graduation Christie started as an apprentice in the engineering shop of the Westinghouse Machine Company.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-graham-christie] After the introduction of its first steam turbine, Christie specialized in that field.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-graham-christie] By 1909 he was research Assistant in Steam and Gas Engineering at the University of Wisconsin, and associate professor of Steam and Gas Engineering by 1914.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-graham-christie] In 1914 he moved to the Johns Hopkins University, where he became associate professor, and later Professor of Engineering until his retirement in 1948, and director of the McCoy College until 1953.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-graham-christie] In 1939-40 Christie served as president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-graham-christie] He was awarded the honorary doctor in engineering by the Stevens Institute of Technology in 1939, and by the Lehigh University in 1940.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-graham-christie] The American Society for Engineering Education awarded Christie the Lamme Gold Medal in 1948, and the first George Westinghouse Gold Medal for engineering by the ASME in 1953.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-graham-christie] At the Johns Hopkins Whiting school of Engineer an annual lecture is held on his behalf, the Alexander Graham Christie Lecture.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] The **Alexander Hamilton Institute** is a former institute for business education in New York City founded in 1909, and dissolved in the 1980s.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] The Alexander Hamilton Institute was a corporation engaged in collecting, organizing and transmitting business information.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] As Dean of New York University School of Commerce, Accounts and Finance, Joseph French Johnson had for many years continually received letters requesting advice on what to read on business.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] These demands came not only from young men, but from mature and able executives, and sometimes even from the most successful business leaders.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] To all such requests Dean Johnson was obliged to reply that the only practical way to study the fundamental principles of business in a systematic manner was to attend the lectures in university schools of commerce.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] At that time the literature of business was scanty and for the most part of doubtful value.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] Working alone, a man could get but little help in his efforts to widen and deepen his knowledge of business principles.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] It became evident that there was a great need for an organized, logical statement of the basic principles on which successful business is founded.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] It was determined to establish an institution which should meet the demand.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] After years of preparation the Alexander Hamilton Institute was established in 1909.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] In selecting the name, it was agreed that none could be so suitable as that of Alexander Hamilton (1757–1804).
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] According to the institute's own account, Hamilton was remembered for his statesmanship, as well as his roles as soldier, financier, author, organizer, and economist.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] The institute described Hamilton as a highly effective manager in the early years of the United States Government.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] When he became the first Secretary of the Treasury in 1789, he found a chaotic government, without money, without credit, and without organization.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] He secured order, provided funds and created prosperity.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] He investigated the industries and directed the early commercial development of the United States.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] The Alexander Hamilton Institute (1921) summarized: "He touched the dead corpse of the public credit, and it sprang upon its feet.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] According to the institute, Hamilton was an effective executive and systematizer; he himself worked out an accounting system for the United States Government which, with but slight modifications, remained in force for more than a hundred years.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] The Modern Business Course and Service is a systematic, time-saving method of bringing to any man's office or home that business knowledge and training which he needs, but which he cannot acquire through his own experience.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] 2. young men who have brains and the ambition to become business executives.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] The publication which is intended for men who want to improve themselves and succeed in their careers.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] These men may or may not have had a thorough education; that is not important; neither is a persons level of education, wealth, or social status.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] Instead they must have the ability and enough commitment to spend a portion of their spare time reading and thinking about business problems and solutions.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] In their 1921 "Forging Ahead in Business" the Alexander Hamilton Institute claimed there are four fundamental activities in every business: Production, Marketing, Financing, and Accounting.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] The accompanying illustration shows the whole field of business charted in such a way as to show clearly the relation of various business activities to each other.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] Economics, the study of business conditions and business policies, is the hub of all business activity.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] Radiating from it are the four grand divisions of business : Production, Marketing, Financing, Accounting.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] These in turn are subdivided into the more detailed activities which they include.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] All business activities may be classified under Production, Marketing, Financing and Accounting.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] For purposes of systematic study, each of these may be subdivided as shown above.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] In addition, there are two important forces which control business : Man and Government.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] For that reason a discussion of the relation between "Business and the Man" and "Business and the Government" naturally forms a part of the survey of modern business.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] The first two and the last two assignments in the Modern Business Course and Service cover these important subjects.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] The arrangement of the subjects has been carefully planned so that the maximum benefit will be derived by following the assignments in their regular order.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] In the chart you see the logical arrangement of these subjects as related to the business world.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] Note that the order in which these subjects are treated in the Course is not according to their arrangement in the chart.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] On the contrary, the more general subjects are first considered; then come the more complex—the specializations and enlargements upon the foundation subjects.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] This plan permits a progressive arrangement that makes for a broad understanding of the science of business.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] Texts, Talks, Lectures, Problems, Monthly Letters, Financial and Trade Reviews, Reports and Service—these are the important features of the Modern Business Course and Service.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] The Alexander Hamilton Institute was referenced disparagingly along with H.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-hamilton-institute] Mencken in *The Sun Also Rises* by Ernest Hemingway (1926).
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Alexander Dreyfoos was the only son of cellist Martha Bullard Whittemore Dreyfoos (1898–1977) and photographer-inventor Alexander W.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] He was of paternal Swiss-Jewish descent.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] He graduated from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) in Cambridge, Massachusetts, in 1954 with a Bachelor of Science focusing on electronics, optics, and physics, assisted by MIT financing after the death of his father.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Having also completed ROTC, Dreyfoos then served in the U.S.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Air Force in Sembach, Germany, 1954–1956, commanding a 40-man photo lab critical to reconnaissance missions at age 22.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Returning home, under the GI Bill he earned an MBA at Harvard Business School in 1958.[4] Dreyfoos earned his pilot's license in 1960, and multiple ratings over time including airline transport pilot (ATP).
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] He had owned six airplanes, including two Citation jets, and two turbine helicopters, all of which he flew single-pilot.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Dreyfoos founded Photo Electronics Corporation (PEC) in 1963, with George W.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Mergens, to address problems in color print reproduction.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] They developed their groundbreaking Video Color Negative Analyzer (VCNA) in Dreyfoos’ Port Chester, New York basement, then set up a factory in a former church in Connecticut.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] The VCNA was marketed worldwide by Eastman Kodak Company.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Dreyfoos moved PEC to Florida in 1969, and in 1970 a motion-picture version of the VCNA earned an Academy Award from the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] From 1990 to 2006, the VCNA was part of the “Information Age: People, Information and Technology” display at the American History Museum of the Smithsonian Institution and remains in its permanent collection.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Dreyfoos later invented the innovative LaserColor Printer and assisted his son, Robert Dreyfoos, in developing a digital version of the VCNA for PEC called the Professional Video Analyzing Computer (PVAC).
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Dreyfoos held ten U.S. and many foreign patents covering his inventions.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Dreyfoos owned television station WPEC TV-12, the CBS affiliate in West Palm Beach, Florida, from 1973 to 1996.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Beginning in 1977, under his direction, his staff developed the world-class Sailfish Marina Resort in Palm Beach Shores, Florida, which he sold in 2004.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] It was the success of PEC that enabled these purchases, and their subsequent sales that enabled Dreyfoos to practice philanthropy, for which he formed The Dreyfoos Group in 1996.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] After founding in 1978 what became the Cultural Council of Palm Beach County, Dreyfoos led efforts that culminated in the 1992 opening of the fully funded Raymond F.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Kravis Center for the Performing Arts, the cultural centerpiece of Palm Beach County.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] He remained its board chair until 2007 and remained a board member for life and its single largest donor at $7,000,000.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] As of June 30, 2016, the Kravis Center ranked in theatre venue ticket sales #11 in the world, #6 in the nation, and #1 in Florida.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] To address his wife Renate's motion sickness, Dreyfoos helped to design their unique SWATH yacht Silver Cloud built by Abeking & Rasmussen in Lemwerder, Germany.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] When launched in 2008, Silver Cloud was the first pleasure yacht with the SWATH design, first used for commercial vessels.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] In 2015 Silver Cloud completed the circumnavigation of the world after Dreyfoos went to extreme measures to travel safely through terrorist-controlled waters.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] For part of the achievement, Dreyfoos received the World SuperYacht 2010 Voyager's Award.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Dreyfoos had been a photographer since childhood and was known for his travel and underwater photos.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] In 2015 he compiled 587 of his favorites in the book *A Photographic Odyssey: Around the World with Alexander W.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Steinhauer), with proceeds supporting the Cultural Council of Palm Beach County (ISBN 978-1-56352-110-2).
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] In 2016 Dreyfoos commissioned his biography, *Alexander W.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Steinhauer and David Randal Allen, with proceeds to The Raymond F.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Kravis Center for the Performing Arts, Inc.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Dreyfoos died on May 28, 2023, at the age of 91.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Dreyfoos made the largest donation in Florida history to a public school when he gave $1,000,000 in 1997 to Palm Beach County School of the Arts, renamed Alexander W.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] His support inspired other philanthropists to fund scholarships and enhancements to the high school.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] The Dreyfoos School of the Arts has been consistently well-viewed.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] News & World Report* ranked it #10 in Florida public high schools and #66 nationally.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] With his financial commitment at its launch in 1998, Dreyfoos became the first founding member of the marine conservation organization International SeaKeepers Society.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] In 2004, Dreyfoos donated $1,000,000 to kick off support of Scripps Florida on the John D.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] MacArthur Campus of Florida Atlantic University in Jupiter, Florida.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] This biomedical research facility of the California-based Scripps Research Institute was joined by the Max Planck Florida Institute for Neuroscience, to which Alexander and Renate Dreyfoos also gave $1,000,000 in 2014.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Dreyfoos was elected as a trustee to both The Scripps Research Institute and Max Planck Florida Institute.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Dreyfoos’ largest gift has been $15,000,000 to MIT for the Stata Center, which consists of two buildings, named for Dreyfoos and Bill Gates.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Dreyfoos dedicated this gift to his late mentor and MIT physics professor, Arthur C.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Dreyfoos had also endowed an Alexander W.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Dreyfoos Professorship at MIT's Media Lab since 1995.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Dreyfoos’ relationship with MIT has been continuous.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] In 2013 the MIT Corporation named the auditorium atop its Media Lab Complex in Dreyfoos’ honor for years of service.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] He remained a Life Member Emeritus of The MIT Corporation.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] One of Dreyfoos' donations to the Raymond F.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Kravis Center for the Performing Arts was his funding of the George W.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alexander-w-dreyfoos-jr] Mergens Memorial Organ, dedicated in 2016, a custom-made electronic virtual pipe organ with a massively parallel processing (MPP) digital computer.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alvin-e-dodd] Dodd was born in Grand Detour, Illinois as son of Alvin Harvey Dodd and Edith (Merrill) Dodd.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alvin-e-dodd] After regular education, he studied engineering at the Armour Institute of Technology, nowadays Illinois Institute of Technology, where he obtained his BS in 1905.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alvin-e-dodd] After graduation Dodd in 1905 started his career as teacher of manual training in Allegheny, Pennsylvania.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alvin-e-dodd] The next year he moved to the Normal School in North Adams, nowadays Massachusetts College of Liberal Arts, where he was appointed head of the manual arts department.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alvin-e-dodd] Two years later he joined the North Bennet Street School, where he was principal until 1912.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alvin-e-dodd] In 1907 Dodd had been elected president of the Eastern Arts Association, and around 1910 was appointed director of the National Society for the Promotion of Industrial Education.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alvin-e-dodd] In those days he became acquainted with Woodrow Wilson at Princeton University, and visited him later in the White House.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alvin-e-dodd] In 1917 Dodd was appointed secretary of the Retail Research Association.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alvin-e-dodd] In a 1916 Address at the National Education Association of the United States, Dodd summarized that "the bill extends to the states the help of the government in establishing vocational education and in training persons to teach it.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alvin-e-dodd] This is to be done by grants of money, and dy establishment of a Federal board of vocational education to work with and through the States in starting this form of education.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alvin-e-dodd] In 1917 Dodd joined the general Staff of the Army, where he took place in the Committee on Classification of Personal.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alvin-e-dodd] In those days Dodd started lecturing in marketing, trade, distribution and industrial problems at Northwestern University, the University of Chicago, Stanford University, and the University of Washington.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alvin-e-dodd] In the later 1920s and 1930s Dodd served in several interim-management positions.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alvin-e-dodd] He was director-general of the Wholesale Dry Goods Institute for two years, assistant to the president of Sears Roebuck for a year, and vice-president of Kroger Grocery and Baking Company in charge of merchandising for another few years.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/alvin-e-dodd] From 1936 to 1948 Dodd was president of the American Management Association, and since July 1, 1948, appointed honorary president.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/dexter-s-kimball] Born in New River, New Brunswick, Kimball grew up in California, and obtained his AB in mechanical engineering from Stanford University in 1896.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/dexter-s-kimball] Kimball had started his career as engineering apprentice in 1881.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/dexter-s-kimball] From 1887 to 1893 he worked at Union Iron Works in San Francisco, California, and from 1896 to 1898.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/dexter-s-kimball] From 1898 to 1901 he was lecturer in machine design at Cornell University.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/dexter-s-kimball] After another working period in industry, he was appointed professor of machine construction at Cornell University.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/dexter-s-kimball] And from 1915 to his retirement in 1936 he was professor of industrial engineering and dean of its College of Engineering.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/dexter-s-kimball] Kimball was elected president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers for the year 1922–23.
[src:dexter-s-kimball/dexter-s-kimball] He was awarded the Worcester Reed Warner Medal in 1933.
